# Experimental Agent System — Development Rules

These rules govern the declarative model in `src/experimental/` and its tests.
They exist to keep the boundary clean between production code and the experimental
layer, and to ensure definitions stay in perfect parity with the concrete agents.

---

## 1. Dependency Direction (hard boundary)

- `src/experimental/*.ts` **must not** duplicate code from `src/*.ts`.
  Import constants and types from `src/*.ts` directly:

  ```typescript
  // ✅ correct
  import { Constants } from '../../../Constants';
  import type { AgentDefinition } from '../../types';

  // ❌ wrong — copy-pasting SYSTEM_PREAMBLE, TAB_NAMES, or any other src/ constant
  const SYSTEM_PREAMBLE = `# EditorLLM Context ...`;
  ```

- `src/*.ts` (production files) **must never** import from `src/experimental/*`.
  The experimental layer is a consumer of production code, never a dependency.

- Test files in `src/__tests__/*.ts` and `src/__tests__/integration/*.ts` **must
  never** import from `src/__tests__/experimental/*.ts`.

---

## 2. SYSTEM_PREAMBLE

The shared agent preamble lives in `Constants.SYSTEM_PREAMBLE` (src/Constants.ts).
Every agent definition builds its system prompt from it:

```typescript
const AGENT_SYSTEM_PROMPT = `${Constants.SYSTEM_PREAMBLE}

# Role: ...`.trim();
```

Never redeclare the preamble string inside a definition file.

---

## 3. W2 Passage Section Title

All W2 (annotateTab) workflows must use `Constants.W2_PASSAGE_SECTION_TITLE` as
the title for the passage content section:

```typescript
{
  title:  Constants.W2_PASSAGE_SECTION_TITLE,
  source: { kind: 'passage' },
}
```

The concrete agents use the same constant. Never use a per-agent variant
(e.g. "Passage To Sweep", "Passage To Audit") — the uniform title lets the LLM
receive the same heading regardless of which agent performs the sweep.

---

## 4. Definition Parity Requirements

Every `AgentDefinition` object must be a perfect mirror of its concrete agent.
The following must match exactly:

| Field | Source of truth |
|---|---|
| `id` | Concrete agent's `getAgentId()` (stable persistence id, not display) |
| `instructionTabName` | `Constants.TAB_NAMES.*` used in the concrete agent's `generateInstructions()` |
| `instructionQualityRubric` | Concrete agent's `getInstructionQualityRubric()` return value (definition string after `.trim()`) |
| `systemPrompt.text` | Concrete agent's `SYSTEM_PROMPT` property (after `.trim()`) |
| `workflows.*.modelTier` | `Constants.MODEL.*` value passed to `callGemini_()` |
| `workflows.*.contextSections` (order + content) | Argument to `buildStandardPrompt()` in the concrete prompt builder |
| `workflows.*.instructions` | Second argument to `buildStandardPrompt()` in the concrete prompt builder |
| `workflows.*.chunkSize` | `CHUNK_SIZE` constant on the concrete agent class |
| `workflows.*.requiresStyleProfile` | Whether the concrete workflow calls `assertStyleProfileValid_()` |

Any discrepancy will cause a parity test failure. When the concrete agent changes,
update the definition first, then verify with `npm run test:experimental`.

---

## 5. Instruction String Separators

All multi-line instruction strings in definitions must use `'\\n'` (the two-character
literal backslash-n) as the `.join()` separator — matching the concrete agents:

```typescript
// ✅ correct
const INSTRUCTIONS = [
  'Line one.',
  'Line two.',
].join('\\n');

// ❌ wrong — actual newline character, diverges from concrete agents
].join('\n');
```

---

## 6. Parity Test Requirements

Every concrete agent must have a corresponding parity test in
`src/__tests__/experimental/agent-parity.test.ts`. Each test must assert:

1. **systemPrompt** — exact string match between concrete and interpreter
2. **userPrompt** — exact string match between concrete and interpreter
3. **tier** — the model tier string (`'fast'` | `'thinking'`)
4. **schema** — deep equality of the JSON schema object (or `undefined` for `plain_markdown`)
5. **processUpdate payload** — at minimum `workflow_type` and `review_tab`
   (catches `instructionTabName` typos that would silently route to the wrong tab)

Tests that only compare `systemPrompt` and `userPrompt` are incomplete.

---

## 7. No New Files Without Definitions and Tests

When adding a new agent to the concrete system:
1. Create `src/experimental/config/agents/<agentName>.ts` with a complete `AgentDefinition`.
2. Add parity tests for every implemented workflow (W1 at minimum).
3. Export the definition from the definition file; import it in the test.

---

## 8. Shared Pure Logic Lives in `src/agentHelpers.ts`

Any logic that is needed by both concrete agents (`BaseAgent` subclasses) and
`AgentInterpreter` — and that has **no GAS side-effects** — belongs in
`src/agentHelpers.ts`, not duplicated or re-implemented in both places.

The test: _can this function be called from a Node.js Jest test with no GAS
globals mocked?_ If yes, it belongs in `agentHelpers.ts`.

Current exports: `assertStyleProfileValid`, `extractMarkdownFromJsonWrapper`,
`buildStandardPrompt`, `validateOps`, `instructionUpdateSchema`,
`annotationOperationsSchema`, `threadRepliesSchema`.

```typescript
// ✅ correct — AgentInterpreter imports from agentHelpers
import { buildStandardPrompt, validateOps } from '../agentHelpers';

// ❌ wrong — re-implementing the same logic as a private static on AgentInterpreter
private static buildStandardPrompt_(...) { ... }
```

When a `protected` method on `BaseAgent` is needed by the interpreter, promote
it to a top-level exported function in `agentHelpers.ts`. Do not re-implement it.

**`agentHelpers.ts` must never call `Tracer.*`, `PropertiesService.*`, or any
other GAS global.** Those are GAS side-effects. Log inside the concrete class
after calling the helper, not inside the helper itself.

---

## 9. extractMarkdownFromJsonWrapper — Applied by Interpreter, Not a PostStep

`extractMarkdownFromJsonWrapper` (from `agentHelpers.ts`) is applied automatically
by `AgentInterpreter.buildInstructionUpdate_` whenever `responseFormat === 'plain_markdown'`.
Do not add it as a `PostStep` kind and do not call it from definition files.

---

## 10. Tab Name Naming Convention

Values in `Constants.TAB_NAMES` must use **Title Case with spaces** — consistent
with how they appear as actual Google Doc tab labels:

```typescript
// ✅ correct
TETHER_INSTRUCTIONS: 'Tether Instructions'
EAR_TUNE:            'EarTune Instructions'

// ❌ wrong — CamelCase with no space (looks like a code identifier, not a tab label)
TETHER_INSTRUCTIONS: 'TetherInstructions'
```

When a tab name is changed, update `Constants.TAB_NAMES`, the ambient declaration
in `Types.ts`, any matching definition `instructionTabName`, and parity tests.
The parity tests' `processUpdate` assertion on `review_tab` will catch most
mismatches automatically.
